Introduction¶

Goals and Perspective¶

In this project, six countries and their GDP will be analyzed. This project aims to identify the relationship between life expectancy and the GDP of a given country.

The data in this project is based on real data and is not real. It has been provided by Codecademy.

The perspective of this project will be that of a data analyst from the World Health Organization (WHO).

The project seeks to answer the following questions:

  • Has life expectancy increased over time in the six nations?
  • Has GDP increased over time in the six nations?
  • Is there a correlation between GDP and life expectancy of a country?
  • What is the average life expectancy in these nations?
  • What is the distribution of that life expectancy?

The project will be broken down into 3 parts.

Loading and Understanding the data¶

In this section, the data and be loaded, and explored for further use.

Analysis¶

This section will answer the questions from the introduction

Conclusion¶

Lastly, the practical use of the data will be discussed. As well as any pitfalls in the data or project.

Loading and understanding the Data¶

This project will primarily use pandas and matplotlib to store and plot the data.

A pandas dataframe or df for short. Is a very powerful data structure that can be used to manipulate data.

The CSV file all_data.csv has 4 columns

  • Country - The name of the country (in this file there are 6)
  • Year - The year the GDP and life expectancy were recorded.
  • Life expectancy - The life expectancy at birth (the number of years a person is expected to live)
  • GDP - Gross domestic product (a measure of all services and goods produced in a country)

Analysis¶

In this section we will answer the questions from the introduction.

Has life expectancy increased over time in the six nations?¶

This is the first question from the introduction. To show the trend of each nation I will create a line graph for all of them. Line graphs are one of the best graphs for showing change over time. Perfect for this question.

In [24]:
years = df['Year'].unique() # all data is from 2000-2015
countries = df["Country"].unique() # list of all countries


for country in countries:
    data = df[df['Country'] == country]  # Filter data for each country
    plt.figure()
    #print(data)
    plt.plot(data["Year"], data["Life expectancy at birth (years)"], label=country, marker='o')  # Plot with dots and lines


    plt.xlabel("Year") 
    plt.ylabel("Life Expectancy")
    plt.xticks(years, rotation=30)
    plt.title(f"{country}'s Life Expectancy")
    plt.legend()

    plt.show()
    plt.close()

Based on these graphs there is a strong increase in expected age for all countries in the years 2000-2015.

To better compare how the countries all increased over time. I am going to plot them together.

Zimbabwe seemed to have the greatest increase in expected age out of all the other countries.

Is there a correlation between GDP and life expectancy of a country?¶

This is the third question from the introduction.

To answer this question we can use a scatter plot. Then statistics to determine the correlation's significance.

In [34]:
countries = df['Country'].astype('category') # list to create plot colorbar and legend
colors = countries.cat.codes 

plt.scatter(df["GDP"], df["Life expectancy at birth (years)"], c=colors, cmap='tab10') # makes a scatter plot
plt.xlabel("GDP")
plt.ylabel("Life Expectancy")
plt.title("Life Expectancy vs GDP")

#creates the color bar on the right with labels
colorbar = plt.colorbar()
colorbar.set_ticks([0, 1, 2, 3, 4, 5])  # 6 countries
colorbar.set_ticklabels(df['Country'].unique())

plt.show()
plt.close()

This scatter plot shows the change in GDP over time with respect to life expectancy.

Zimbabwe seems to have no change even though in previous sections there were clear changes. This is most likely because the other countries have much higher GDP's and life expectancy.

Let us use a Pearson coefficient to determine if there's a correlation.

In [36]:
correlation_coefficient, p_value = st.pearsonr(df['GDP'], df['Life expectancy at birth (years)']) # returns the coefficient and p-value

print("Pearson Correlation Coefficient =",  round(correlation_coefficient,4))
print("P-value =", round(p_value,4))

Pearson Correlation Coefficient = 0.3432
P-value = 0.0006

A coefficient of 0.3432 indicated a weak correlation. With a p-value less than a 1% level of significance(0.01) it is statistically significant.

Though Zimbabwe as an outlier may affect this coefficient. In the scatter plot, it seems there is no change in GDP. At least on the same scale as the rest of the countries.

To potentially solve this we will use calculate the coefficient of each country on its own.

In [38]:
years = df['Year'].unique() # list 2000-2015
countries = df["Country"].unique() # list of all countries

# loops over every country in the data, subsets it, and calculates the correlation coefficient
for country in countries:
    country_data = df[df['Country'] == country]
    correlation_coefficient, p_value =  st.pearsonr( country_data['GDP'],  country_data['Life expectancy at birth (years)'])
    print(f"Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of {country} = {round(correlation_coefficient,4)}")
    print(f"{country}'s P-value = {round(p_value,4)}")
    print()

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of Chile = 0.9499
Chile's P-value = 0.0

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of China = 0.9085
China's P-value = 0.0

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of Germany = 0.9327
Germany's P-value = 0.0

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of Mexico = 0.9322
Mexico's P-value = 0.0

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of United States of America = 0.9817
United States of America's P-value = 0.0

Pearson's Correlation Coefficient of Zimbabwe = 0.9662
Zimbabwe's P-value = 0.0

While getting the correlation coefficient for every country on its own does not tell us the whole trend of all six.

It does tell us that for each country, there is a very strong positive correlation between GDP and life expectancy for each country. And with a p-value near 0 for all of them, they are all statistically significant.

Conclusion¶

In this project, we analyzed data on GDP and life expectancy in six different countries.

Key Findings¶

We were able to answer all of the questions posed in the introduction.

  1. Has life expectancy increased over time in the six nations?

    Yes, it has increased over time for every nation. Zimbabwe had the most growth.

  2. Has GDP increased over time in the six nations?

    Yes GDP increased for every nation over time. Again Zimbabwe had the most growth.

  3. Is there a correlation between GDP and life expectancy of a country?

    Individually every country has a strong positive correlation that is statistically significant.

  4. What is the average life expectancy in these nations?

    The average life expectancy in every nation but Zimbabwe was in the mid-high 70s. Zimbabwe has the lowest at 50.

  5. What is the distribution of that life expectancy?

    The data is very left-skewed. Meaning that most of the data is on the higher end. No other country other than Zimbabwe had a life expectancy lower than 70.

Discussion¶

I expected life expectancy and GDP to be correlated. The wealthier a country to better healthcare it tends to have. The more it can spend on hospitals and so on. This is a very important relationship because it can help us determine the average life expectancy of a nation based on its GDP or vice versa.

However, correlation does not imply causation. There are likely a lot of other factors that play into both GDP and life expectancy. To get more accurate results more data than just GDP and life expectancy would be needed.

I was surprised to see the growth of Zimbabwe. While every other nation had a slow and steady increase Zimabwe has explosive growth.

I also expected that GDP and life expectancy would increase over time. The time this data is set in(2000-2015) was a time of worldwide economic growth.

Further Analysis¶

This dataset included only six countries. Adding more countries with lower GDP and life expectancies similar to Zimabsbwe would help outliers not affect the data. It would also allow for more accurate findings.

When determining a correlation between GDP and life expectancy of all six counties, a better method would be to create a regression model. To better create a multiple regression model, having other variables that may affect life expectancy would be beneficial. However, that is beyond the ability of this dataset and the scope of this project.

Zimbabwe in 2008 had massive growth both in GDP and life expectancy. This trend should be looked into in future analyses.
